{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Chandler Moisen","author":"Chandler Moisen"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"e6a26468-66ac-5c0d-81fd-52ff19f991c5","excerpt":"When I began my career as a software engineer, I suffered the misconception that software development was a straight-forward, unidirectional, two-step system…","html":"<p>When I began my career as a software engineer, I suffered the misconception that software development was a straight-forward, unidirectional, two-step system:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Product devises feature</li>\n<li>Engineering ships feature</li>\n</ol>\n<p><a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/9d1e5ecc679f0e40148468208b0476c3/eb3e8/the-software-development-process.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 161px;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 149.68944099378882%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    ></span>\n    <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"the software development process\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/9d1e5ecc679f0e40148468208b0476c3/eb3e8/the-software-development-process.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/9d1e5ecc679f0e40148468208b0476c3/cf440/the-software-development-process.png 148w,\n/static/9d1e5ecc679f0e40148468208b0476c3/eb3e8/the-software-development-process.png 161w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 161px) 100vw, 161px\"\n      />\n  </span>\n  </a></p>\n<p>This misconception led to a series of pernicious beliefs in how I approached daily work.</p>\n<h3>Pernicious Belief 1: Only Shipping Is Valuable</h3>\n<p>Engineering was only responsible for shipping as shipping was the most visible step when engineering’s value was realized. An engineer’s value to the organization was worthless until they smashed that “Merge pull request” button.</p>\n<p><a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/18e3b7452093a4626c66a51649fbc0a9/de370/merge-button.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 209px;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 24.880382775119617%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    ></span>\n    <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"merge pull request button\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/18e3b7452093a4626c66a51649fbc0a9/de370/merge-button.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/18e3b7452093a4626c66a51649fbc0a9/cf440/merge-button.png 148w,\n/static/18e3b7452093a4626c66a51649fbc0a9/de370/merge-button.png 209w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 209px) 100vw, 209px\"\n      />\n  </span>\n  </a></p>\n<h3>Pernicious Belief 2: Engineers Are Paid To Code</h3>\n<p>The majority of an engineer’s time should be spent inside their IDE. After all, this is why engineers were paid: to produce text files full of variables and functions that, taken together, comprised a feature that product determined valuable.</p>\n<p>If I finished a day at work without having made a commit, I took this as a personal failure.</p>\n<h3>Pernicious Belief 3</h3>\n<p>Pushing back against the straight-forward, unidirectional, two-step system is akin to heresy. The product team knows the customer the best and engineering is supposed to carry out product’s vision.</p>\n<p>Engineers are supposed to say “yes”. Say “yes” to product, say “yes” to the users, say “yes” to requirement changes, etc.</p>\n<h2>The Ease of “Yes”</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>As a dev, you are inclined to code</li>\n<li>Inclined to build, to “deliver value”</li>\n<li>Users are waiting for fixes and features</li>\n<li>Very very easy to say, “Yes” to everything</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>The Challenge of “No”</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>Saying “no” means value is not delivered</li>\n<li>Steps are not taken towards quarterly goals</li>\n<li>Your sprint velocity suffers</li>\n<li>You anger your product and design teams who invested hours in specs and wireframes</li>\n<li>Hard to stop organizational momentum when leadership is behind something</li>\n<li>Takes confidence to say no</li>\n</ol>","frontmatter":{"title":"Saying \"No\"","date":"December 23, 2019"}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"slug":"/saying-no/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/airtable-bootstrapping-made-easy/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Airtable: Bootstrapping Made Easy"}},"next":null}}